>[Question]
>Dear Dr. Math:
>
>My question is how to prove if I let a,b and c be complex constants 
>then the quadratic equation a*z^2 + b*z + c=0 has one or two roots. 
>Pleas help I am not for sure where to start. Is a complex constant 
>the same thing as a complex number.
>
>[Difficulty]
>
>
>[Thoughts]
>

Hello Steve,

My opinion is that to say "let a, b, and c be complex constants,"  means that a, b, and c 
can be complex numbers.

One can complete the square on a*z^2+b*z+c=0, whether a, b, and c are complex or real.  
The argument would be precisely the same as in the real case.


